The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 F1, cricket security up 

London: Security will be tightened for Sundays one-day International between England and Australia and the British Formula One Grand Prix after more than 50 people were killed in Thursdays bomb blasts in London. 

A spokesperson for the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) confirmed the match at Lords in central London would go ahead with metal detectors employed to search spectators. 

There will be increased police presence and everyone and their bags will be searched, she said. 

Security has also been stepped up at Silverstone, venue of the GP, with cars and bags searched at entrance points. 

I think I speak on behalf of everyone involved in Formula One, that we are obviously deeply shocked and saddened by what has happened in London, said BARs Jenson Button, the only English Formula One driver. 

It is obviously a difficult way to start the weekend for everyone, but we are going to try to put the best show on we can for the fans in the situation we have. On mainland Europe, Tour de France cyclists held a minutes silence in memory of the victims of of the explosions. (REUTERS) 




